le effect on one area of law and regulation: human rights.Universal Human Rights and Extraterritorial Obligations examines both the international and domestic foundations of human rights law. What other contemporary human rights debates have almost totally ignored is that in an increasingly interdependent world—where public and private international actors have great influence on the lives of individuals everywhere—it is insufficient to assess only the record of domestic governments in human rights. It is equally important to assess the effect of actions taken by intergovernmental organizations, international private entities, and foreign states.From this standpoint, contributors to this book address how states' actions or omissions may affect the prospects of individuals in foreign states and asks important questions: To what extent do agricultural policies of rich countries influence the right to food in poorer countries? How do decisions to screen asylum seekers outside state borders affect refugee rights? How does cooperation among different states in the "war on terror" influence individuals' rights to be free from torture? This volume presents a brief for a more complex and updated approach to the protection of human rights worldwide.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aHuman rights. 0aInternational and municipal law. 4aHuman Rights. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Human Rights.2bisacsh  aHuman Rights.  aLaw.  aPolitical Science.1 aBueno de Mesquita, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCahill, Amanda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrey, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGammeltoft-­Hansen, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGibney, Mark, econtributor.4